      "comment": {
        "comments": [
          {
            "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12675859/comment/13805537",
            "id": "13805537",
            "author": {
              "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jlowe",
              "name": "jlowe",
              "key": "jlowe",
              "avatarUrls": {
                "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452",
                "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452",
                "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452",
                "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"
              },
              "displayName": "Jason Darrell Lowe",
              "active": true,
              "timeZone": "America/Chicago"
            },
            "body": "One idea is to persist the ACLs for an application underneath the application directory in the log directory tree.  That has the benefit of  automatically removing the persisted ACL data when an application's logs are removed (and thus ACLs are no longer needed).  Restoring of application ACLs potentially could be lazily performed as well if it isn't cached in memory.",
            "updateAuthor": {
              "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jlowe",
              "name": "jlowe",
              "key": "jlowe",
              "avatarUrls": {
                "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452",
                "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452",
                "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452",
                "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"
              },
              "displayName": "Jason Darrell Lowe",
              "active": true,
              "timeZone": "America/Chicago"
            },
            "created": "2013-10-25T18:07:49.107+0000",
            "updated": "2013-10-25T18:07:49.107+0000"
          },
          {
            "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12675859/comment/13969626",
            "id": "13969626",
            "author": {
              "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jlowe",
              "name": "jlowe",
              "key": "jlowe",
              "avatarUrls": {
                "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452",
                "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452",
                "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452",
                "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"
              },
              "displayName": "Jason Darrell Lowe",
              "active": true,
              "timeZone": "America/Chicago"
            },
            "body": "YARN-1354 is recovering application ACLs as part of recovering applications, so this should be covered by that change.  We can reopen this if we decide to pursue the idea of persisting the ACLs separately under the application log directory and do a lazy lookup of ACLs from the filesystem.",
            "updateAuthor": {
              "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jlowe",
              "name": "jlowe",
              "key": "jlowe",
              "avatarUrls": {
